    <body>
        <header>
            <h1>Codecademy Cheat Sheet: CSS Selectors</h1>
            <h2>Selector Types</h2>
        </header>
        <div id="table1">
            <table>
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Selector example</td>
                        <td>Name</td>
                        <td>Description</td>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <span class="css">Example: h1</span>
                            
                        </td>
                        <td>Type Selector</td>
                        <td>The type selector does what its name suggests. It selects a HTML element type to apply style to.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <span class="css">Example: *</span>
                        </td>
                        <td>Universal Selector</td>
                        <td>This selector is used to select all elements of any type. Can change all fonts or color on a page, and is used to reset to default browers settings.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <span class="css">Example: .Code</span>
                        </td>
                        <td>Class selector</td>
                        <td>Used to target a specific class attribute assigned to an HTML element. Must put a period (.) before the class attribute.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <span class="css">Example: #idselector</span>
                        </td>
                        <td>Id selector</td>
                        <td>An id selector is similar to a class selector, but Id selectors are very specific. You can have more than one HTML attribute with the same class selector. It is recomemded that you keep Id selectors specific and do not repeat the Id attribute value more than once. </td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
             </table>
        </div>
        <h2>Rules on specificity and Chaining selectors</h2>
        <div id="table2">
            <table>
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Name</td>
                        <td>Description</td>
                    </tr>
                </thead>           
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <span class="css">Specificity</span>
                        </td>
                        <td>The best practice is to style an element with the lowest degree of specificity, so if an element needs a new style it is easier to override. Selectors by specificity:
                            <ol>
                                <li>Id</li>
                                <li>Class</li>
                                <li>Type</li>
                            </ol>
                        </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>
                            <span class="css">Chaining selectors</span>
                        </td>
                        <td>Adding more than one selector increased specificity. An &lt;h1&gt; and &lt;p&gt; together is more specific than an individual id selector.</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
    </body>
</html>
